AI-Learning - Didn’t “start from scratch” to move into AI engineering.
I just looked at what I already knew… and built from there.

If you’re a software engineer, you’re closer than you think.

You already understand:
→ APIs
→ System design
→ Deployment.
→ Testing
→ CI/CD
→ Version control

The shift isn’t about learning everything new.
It’s about **reframing what you know for AI systems.**

But a few things hit me the hard way:
→ LLMs are not databases. Same input ≠ same output
→ Don’t jump into building full systems… test the model first
→ Changing models (like GPT → Claude) can break behavior silently

================================================================
What actually worked for me was keeping it simple and structured:
================================================================
**Weeks 1–4**
Focused only on LLM basics + prompt engineering
Built my first RAG from scratch (no frameworks)

**Weeks 5–8**
Started working with agents
Learned function calling, retrieval, structured outputs
And most importantly, how to evaluate outputs

**Weeks 9–12**
Took things to production
Latency, caching, monitoring, error handling
That’s where things started to feel real

No fancy roadmap.
No 50-course checklist.

Just consistent building + understanding how these systems behave.

If you’re waiting to feel “ready” to switch,
you probably already are.

Just start.
